escot and Laurence Magloire—none of whom identify as Vodou practitioners. In so doing, Tinsley offers a model of queer black feminist theory that creates new possibilities for decolonizing queer studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAfrican diaspora in art. 0aBlacksxSexual behaviorzHaiti. 0aFeminism. 0aGender identityzHaiti. 0aHomosexuality. 0aLegendszHaiti. 0aQueer theory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106963320 cprintz978082237030740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822372080423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822372080/original  a978-3-11-069633-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles